<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910405-0051</DOCNO><DOCID>910405-0051.</DOCID><HL>   Army Expected to Pick   Team for Helicopter Pact</HL><DATE>04/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   BA MD TXT UTX</CO><MS>CONGLOMERATES (CGL)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><GV>DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)</GV><RE>CONNECTICUT (CT)MISSOURI (MO)RHODE ISLAND (RI)WASHINGTON (WA)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Army is expected to announce today theteam of companies to build its next-generation lighthelicopter, a contract potentially worth tens of billions ofdollars.   Battling for the award is a team composed of McDonnellDouglas Corp. and Textron Inc.'s Bell division against a teammade up of Boeing Co. and United Technologies Corp.'sSikorsky subsidiary.</LP><TEXT>   The Army had said yesterday afternoon that theannouncement of a winner would be delayed until next week&quot;pending further reporting&quot; to senior Defense Departmentofficials. Officials indicated that even though the Army hadmade its selection, Defense Secretary Dick Cheney hasn't beenfully briefed yet. And industry officials said the Pentagonacquisition office may have had some last-minute questionsfor the Army about the structure of the contract.   But late last night, spokesmen for both teams said theyhad received calls from the general in charge of the program,indicating that an announcement would come today after all.   The winning team will be awarded a $2.7 billion contractto demonstrate and validate its technology through thebuilding of several prototypes, the Army said. That will leadto a full-scale development program. Ultimately, the Pentagonhas plans to buy 1,292 light helicopters at a rate of 120 ayear. They would replace the current fleet of AH-1, OH-6 andOH-58 helicopters at a cost of $34.2 billion.</TEXT></DOC>